<h2><a name="read" id="read">read</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    istream<span class="sy0">&amp;</span> istream<span class="sy0">::</span><span class="me2">read</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">char</span><span class="sy0">*</span> buffer<span class="sy0">,</span> streamsize num <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;</pre>
<p>

The function read() is used with input streams, and reads num bytes from the
stream before placing them in buffer. If <acronym title="End of file">EOF</acronym> is encountered, read() stops,
leaving however many bytes it put into buffer as they are.
For example:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">     <span class="kw4">struct</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
       <span class="kw4">int</span> height;
       <span class="kw4">int</span> width;
     <span class="br0">&#125;</span> rectangle;
&nbsp;
     input_file.<span class="me1">read</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="kw4">char</span> <span class="sy0">*</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="sy0">&amp;</span>rectangle<span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">sizeof</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span>rectangle<span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;
     <span class="kw1">if</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span> input_file.<span class="me1">bad</span><span class="br0">&#40;</span><span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span> <span class="br0">&#123;</span>
       cerr <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="st0">&quot;Error reading data&quot;</span> <span class="sy0">&lt;&lt;</span> endl;
       exit<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="nu19">0</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;
     <span class="br0">&#125;</span></pre>
<p>
